 Collaboration with Learning-Disabled Neighbours and Partners -- t11 Intellectual Disability in South Africa Affirmative Stories and Photographs from the Grahamstown Lunatic Asylum, 1890–1920 -- t12 Pathways to Disrupt Eugenics in Higher Education -- t13 “You Just Want to Do What’s Right” Staff Collusion in Institutional Abuse of People with Learning Disabilities -- tPART 3 Social Justice and Place Making in the Absence of Sites of Conscience -- t14 A Place to Have a Cup of Cofee: Remembering and Returning to a Dismantled Psychiatric Hospita -- t15 A Sense of Community within a Site of Amplified Stigma The Strange Case of Spookers -- t16 Naming Streets in a Post-asylum Landscape Cultural Heritage Processes and the Politics of Ableism -- t17 “We Bent the Motorway” Community Action on Exminster Hospital -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInto the twenty-first century, millions of disabled people and people experiencing mental distress were segregated from the rest of society and confined to residential institutions. Deinstitutionalization – the closure of these sites and integration of former residents into the community – has become increasingly commonplace. But this project is unfinished. Sites of Conscience explores use of the concept of sites of conscience, which involves place-based memory activities such as walking tours, survivor-authored social histories, and performances and artistic works in or generated from sites of systemic suffering and injustice. These activities offer new ways to move forward from the unfinished deinstitutionalization project and its failures. Covering diverse national contexts, this volume proposes that acknowledging the memories and lived experiences of former residents – and keeping histories and social heritage of institutions alive rather than simply closing sites – holds the greatest potential for recognition, accountability, and action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMemorialization. 0aMentally illxDeinstitutionalization. 0aPeople with disabilitiesxDeinstitutionalization. 0aPsychiatric hospitals. 0aSocial justice. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh1 aAltermark, Niklas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndrews, Gavin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaur, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalabria, Verusca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChowdhury, Matilda Svensson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemke, Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, Rob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIngham, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKearns, Robin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Evadne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLindbom, Helena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Justine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Nicole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, David T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoon, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlessis, Rory Du, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPunzi, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPunzi, Elisabeth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aReaume, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov